[3/6]

In combination, the story can be pretty dumb and the character motivations could be a lot better. Like at the start of the story, they speak about not wanting to do anything, which I feel could have tied in and even be a focal point, but it ends up being ignored for this

1. #DoctorStrange was such a disappointment. The first movie was an underrated gem that sets up Dr. Strange to have unique powers and cinematic styling. This movie shows how homogenized the Marvel movies have become and uses Dr. Strange as a vehicle to setup other characters

2. Most of the magic was so generic and unimaginative. Whether a Marvel movie uses sci-fi weapons or magic spells, it all looks like the same uninspired CGI energy blasts. #DoctorStrange originally made it seem like magic would be a quirky, creatively satisfying curiosity

3. Now the line between science and magic has become so blurred the two are literally the same and each has lost their identity. Overall the "less is more" approach would have been better. #DoctorStrange

4. There are a couple moments when magic isn't used as a shield/blast/beam and those parts of the action sequences are the most fun and a reminder of what a better thought out use of #DoctorStrange's powerset could have looked like.

7. Instead, the MCU continues to attempt to build more and more epic crossovers to the point where movies are bloated messes where the best parts are brief moments of cheap fan service. #DoctorStrange deserves better than to be a side character in his own film.

8. Overall, #DoctorStrange is a bottom tier addition to the MCU that will let down fans of the character. The story is ruined by PIS, bloat, and pacing. The action is derivative save for one or two short sequences and foreshadows a poor future for the MCU.
